      <div xml:id="NA187-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaimakaṉ (ET: /) pakaṟkuṟi vantu mīḷvāṉatu celavu nōkkit talaimakaḷ taṉ uḷḷē colluvāḷāyc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE said as one speaking to her own heart with respect to the going of HIM who returned after having come to the daytime tryst.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA187">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            neytal kūmpa niḻalkuṇak koḻukak</l>
<l>            kalcēr maṇṭilañ civantunilan taṇiyap</l>
<l>            palpūṅ kāṉalu malkiṉ ṟaṉṟē</l>
<l>            yiṉamaṇi volippap poḻutupaṭap pūṭṭi</l>
<l>            meymmali kāmat tiyāntoḻu toḻiyat </l>
<l>            tēruñ celpuṟa maṟaiyu mūro</l>
<l>            ṭiyāṅkā vatuko ṟāṉē tēmpaṭa</l>
<l>            vūtuvaṇ ṭimiruṅ kōtai mārpiṉ</l>
<l>            miṉṉivar koṭumpūṭ koṇkaṉō</l>
<l>            ṭiṉṉakai mēvanā māṭiya poḻilē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent">        While the blue waterlilies close, while the shadow falls eastward,</l>
<l rend="indent">        while the stone-joining [sun-]disk reddens [and] the ground is appeased,</l>
<l>    the many-flowered seashore-grove has come to rest<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">alkiṉṟaṉṟē</term>: T.V.G. reads here <term xml:lang="ta">malkiṉṟaṉṟu</term>, which he explains as "decreasing in beauty" (which is the semantic opposite of the usual increasing).</note></l>
<l>    and,</l>
<l rend="indent2">        [horses] yoked, as [day-]time is fading, so that the assorted bells sound,</l>
<l>    the moving back of the chariot is vanishing,<note place="foot">Syntax is peculiar here. While the form <term xml:lang="ta">maṟaiyum</term> actually would guide us to take it as a peyareccam dependant on <term xml:lang="ta">ūroṭu</term>, the double marking with <term xml:lang="ta">–um, kāṉalum ... tērum</term>, has induced me to read a coordination of two independent clauses. Otherwise we have a caesura only after the 3rd line: "... the seashore-grove too has come to rest. What will become of it, along with the village where the moving back of [his] chariot too is vanishing, ..."</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">        for us with desire much in [our] body to stay behind in reverence.</l>
<l>    What will become of it, along with the village,</l>
<l rend="indent">        – of the grove where we played, when [he?] wished for a sweet smile,</l>
<l rend="indent">        with the man from the sea with curved ornaments, from which flashes rise,</l>
<l rend="indent">        on [his] chest with a garland where bees hum, filling themselves up</l>
<l rend="indent4">            so that there will be honey?</l>
        </lg>
